  "text": "We assume that keratinocytes are initially present in the epidermal region outside the wounded area, x ! L x , y ! jL y , while fibroblasts and the ECM are present in the region y , 0, as well as the dermal region outside the wounded area, x ! L x , y jL y . In our model, interleukin-1 and KGF are produced by keratinocytes and fibroblasts, respectively, and so we assume that they are initially absent in the wounded area and present outside. As PDGF and TGF-b are produced by macrophages and platelets present in the fibrin clot [CITATION_1] , we assume that they are initially present in the wounded area and absent outside. For the GFs we use no-flux boundary conditions along each boundary, while for the keratinocytes and fibroblasts we use no-flux boundary conditions along x ¼ 0 and y ¼ L y , and Dirichlet boundary conditions along x ¼ ð1 þ hÞL x and y ¼ ÀhL y . These initial and boundary conditions are simulated using steep tanh functions and are detailed in the electronic supplementary material. We now present a set of numerical results obtained [CITATION_2] using this model that describe different wound healing outcomes. We include three movies in the electronic supplementary material that show the evolving densities of keratinocytes over the entire domain for each outcome, illustrating the development of the invasive 'tongue' and the subsequent migration of these cells across the wound.",
